Among the hundreds of underwater locations I have seen, a handful of these landscapes has profoundly touched me.
I saw the first of these landscapes about 10 years ago, off the wild and rugged coast of South Africa.
Every summer, huge schools of sardines move north, a mass migration phenomenon known as the Sardine Run.
A wild race of these fish
where hungry and agile hordes of predators chase them.
Common dolphins hunt together and manage to isolate sardines from the main school, creating small schools.
They dive and herd the fish upwards, against the surface, and rush to enjoy their wriggling feast.
The sharks follow closely.
For many people, sharks and dolphins are sworn enemies, but during the Sardine Run, they coexist.
In fact, dolphins help sharks to feed more efficiently.
Without the dolphins, the small schools created are more sparse, and the sharks often end up with a "sardine doughnut" or a mouthful of water.
I had some lively moments with the sharks during the Sardine Run, but I know they don't see me as prey.
I receive blows and am jostled like all the other participants in this brawling banquet.
Let's leave the African coasts and head east, across the vastness of the Indian Ocean to the Maldives, an archipelago of coral islands.
During the monsoon season, manta rays from across the archipelago make their way to a tiny islet in Baa Atoll called Hanifaru.
Armies of crustaceans, most smaller than a marble, are the staple food of manta rays.
When plankton concentrations are low, manta rays feed alone and perform backward somersaults, looping like a puppy chasing its tail.
When the density of plankton increases, the rays line up in single file and form these long chains. Every delicious morsel that escapes the first is gobbled up by the second or the next one.
When the concentration of plankton reaches its peak, manta rays swim ever closer in a rotating movement through which they feed.
As they swirl in this tight formation, the column of manta rays creates its own vortex, sucking in and bringing plankton right into the cavernous mouths of the rays.
The experience of diving among these countless rays is absolutely unforgettable.
The first time I photographed Hanifaru, the site was unprotected and threatened by development.
I have worked with NGOs such as Manta Trust, and my photos have helped make Hanifaru a marine protected area.
Fishermen from the neighboring islands hunted these manta rays, using their skin to make traditional drums.
Today, they are the most fervent conservationists, and manta rays contribute over 8 million dollars to the Maldivian economy each year.
