Bassas da India is largely unknown. It is a tiny coral spot in the Mozambique Channel.
Its barrier forms a shield that protects its inner lagoon, a nursery for Galapagos sharks.
These sharks are anything but shy, even during the day.
Something told me they would be even bolder and more numerous at night.
I found myself facing more sharks than ever, gathered around a simple outcrop.
Photographing and sharing moments like these reminds me why I chose this path.
Not long ago, I was working on a project in Baja California for National Geographic.
Halfway down the Pacific coast lies San Ignacio Lagoon, where the gray whale comes to give birth.
For a century, this coast has been the scene of a systematic massacre, with more than 20,000 gray whales killed, leaving only a few hundred survivors.
Today, the descendants of these same whales play at the surface with their offspring, and they even interact with us.
This species has remarkably thrived.
On the other side of the peninsula lies Cabo Pulmo, a sleepy fishing village.
Decades of overfishing have brought them to the brink of collapse.
In 1995, local fishermen convinced the authorities to make their waters a marine reserve.
But what happened next is nothing short of a miracle.
In 2005, after just a decade of protection, scientists recorded the largest increase in fish.
